From: PS3 Custom Toolchain
Subject: [PATCH] gcc/convert: use unsigned intermediate for pointer-to-int cast

When converting a pointer to an integer type, convert_to_integer_1
already comments that the intermediate type should be an unsigned
integer of the pointer's precision.  The code, however, passes 0
(signed) for the unsignedp flag in the type_for_size call:

    expr = fold_build1 (CONVERT_EXPR,
                        lang_hooks.types.type_for_size
                          (TYPE_PRECISION (intype), 0),
                        expr);

Under the default ILP32 hybrid ABI on powerpc64-ps3-elf, pointers are
32-bit but live in 64-bit GPRs.  When user code writes (uint64_t)ptr
or otherwise casts a pointer to a wider unsigned type, the conversion
flows through this code path.  With the signed intermediate type, GCC
sign-extends the pointer value to 64 bits; for any pointer whose bit
31 is set (e.g. user-mode stack addresses in the 0xd0xxxxxx range)
that produces 0xffffffff_xxxxxxxx, and the upper 0xffffffff bits
propagate into subsequent arithmetic or memory access.  Concrete
example surfaced today: the lv2 syscall wrappers' (u64)ptr cast
landed sign-extended addresses in syscall argument registers.

Change the intermediate to unsigned, matching the comment.  The
existing 32-bit precision cases keep their two-step convert; the
behavior is now identical to what the comment promised all along.

--- a/gcc/convert.cc
+++ b/gcc/convert.cc
@@ -644,7 +644,7 @@
 	return build1 (CONVERT_EXPR, type, expr);
       expr = fold_build1 (CONVERT_EXPR,
 			  lang_hooks.types.type_for_size
-			    (TYPE_PRECISION (intype), 0),
+			    (TYPE_PRECISION (intype), 1),
 			  expr);
       return fold_convert (type, expr);
 
